A bit of an odd case, but do you think this is behaving correctly?

```css
.foo {
    .bar:not(&) {
        color: red;
    }
}
```

I would have expected this to produce:

```css
.bar:not(.foo) {
    color: red;
}
```

Instead it seems to ignore the ampersand inside `:not()`:

![Screen Shot 2021-09-09 at 2 38 46 PM](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1432010/132766222-81cd3642-a8e4-4468-a534-94a7ed806978.png)

SCSS
```scss
main {
   background-color: yellow;

  :is(& > *) {
     background-color: blue;
  }

  :where(& > *) {
     background-color: red;
  }
}
```

Compiled CSS
```css
main {
   background-color: yellow;
}

:is(main > *) {
   background-color: blue;
}

main :where(& > *) {
   background-color: red;
}
```

Using `"sass": "^1.49.8"`

